section_list.name: PDU SESSION RESOURCE SETUP REQUEST
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF and is used to request the NG-RAN node to assign resources on Uu and NG-U for one or several PDU session resources.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority - Section Description: This IE contains the service priority as defined in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority IE Semantics: Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 256 as the lowest priority

9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU - Section Description: This IE contains a 5GC - UE or UE - 5GC message that is transferred without interpretation in the NG-RAN node. 9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU IE Semantics: The content is defined in TS 24.501 [26].
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU - Section Description: This IE contains a 5GC - UE or UE - 5GC message that is transferred without interpretation in the NG-RAN node. 9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU IE Semantics: The content is defined in TS 24.501 [26].
9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].
9.2.1.1 PDU Session Resource Setup Request Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the PDU Session Resource Setup Request Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.1.

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per UE which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and a subscription parameter provided by the AMF to the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows.

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

section_list.name: PDU SESSION RESOURCE SETUP RESPONSE
aoa:
This message is sent by the NG-RAN node as a response to the request to assign resources on Uu and NG-U for one or several PDU session resources.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.2.1.2 PDU Session Resource Setup Response Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the PDU Session Resource Setup Response Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.2.
├─PDU Session Resource Failed to Setup List
│  └─PDU Session Resource Failed to Setup Item
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.2.1.2 PDU Session Resource Setup Unsuccessful Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the PDU Session Resource Setup Unsuccessful Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.16.

9.3.1.3 Criticality Diagnostics - Section Description: The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

section_list.name: PDU SESSION RESOURCE RELEASE COMMAND

9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority - Section Description: This IE contains the service priority as defined in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority IE Semantics: Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 256 as the lowest priority

9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU - Section Description: This IE contains a 5GC - UE or UE - 5GC message that is transferred without interpretation in the NG-RAN node. 9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU IE Semantics: The content is defined in TS 24.501 [26].
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.2.1.3 PDU Session Resource Release Command Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the PDU Session Resource Release Command Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.12.

9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.

section_list.name: INITIAL CONTEXT SETUP REQUEST
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to request the setup of a UE context.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.3.21 AMF Name - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify the AMF (see TS 38.300 [8]). It may also be used as a human readable name of the AMF.

9.2.2.1 - UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE - ifPDUsessionResourceSetup: This IE shall be present if the PDU Session Resource Setup List IE is present. 9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per UE which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and a subscription parameter provided by the AMF to the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows.

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s
├─Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE
9.3.1.15 Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for e.g. RRC_INACTIVE configuration.
9.3.3.23 UE Identity Index Value - Section Description: This IE is used by the NG-RAN node to calculate the Paging Frame as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.3.23 Index Length 10 IE Semantics: Coded as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.1.90 Paging DRX - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging DRX as defined in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].

9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer - Section Description: This IE is used to assist NG-RAN to generate corresponding timer for periodic RNA update for RRC_INACTIVE UEs. 9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer IE Semantics: Bits 5 to 1 represent the binary coded timer value. Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.
9.3.1.23 MICO Mode Indication - Section Description: This IE indicates that the UE is configured with MICO mode by the AMF.
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.93 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: Included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.
9.3.1.154 Paging eDRX Information - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging eDRX parameters as defined in TS 36.304 [29].

9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].
9.3.1.86 UE Security Capabilities - Section Description: This IE defines the supported algorithms for encryption and integrity protection in the UE.

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EEA0, "first bit" – 128-EEA1, "second bit" – 128-EEA2, "third bit" – 128-EEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EIA0, "first bit" – 128-EIA1, "second bit" – 128-EIA2, "third bit" – 128-EIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.87 Security Key - Section Description: This IE is used to apply security in the NG-RAN for different scenarios as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key IE Semantics: Key material for NG-RAN node or Next Hop Key as defined in TS 33.501 [13]
9.3.1.14 Trace Activation - Section Description: This IE defines parameters related to a trace session activation.

9.3.1.14 NG-RAN Trace ID IE Semantics: This IE is composed of the following: Trace Reference defined in TS 32.422 [11] (leftmost 6 octets, with PLMN information encoded as in 9.3.3.1), and Trace Recording Session Reference defined in TS 32.422 [11] (last 2 octets).

9.3.1.14 Interfaces to Trace IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an NG-RAN node interface: first bit = NG-C, second bit = Xn-C, third bit = Uu, fourth bit = F1-C, fifth bit = E1: other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates 'should be traced'. Value '0' indicates 'should not be traced'.

Value “1” indicates “activate” and value “0” indicates “do not activate”.

section_list.name: UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to provide UE Context information changes to the NG-RAN node.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority - Section Description: This IE contains the service priority as defined in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority IE Semantics: Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 256 as the lowest priority

9.3.1.87 Security Key - Section Description: This IE is used to apply security in the NG-RAN for different scenarios as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key IE Semantics: Key material for NG-RAN node or Next Hop Key as defined in TS 33.501 [13]

9.3.1.61 Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority - Section Description: This IE is used to define local configuration for RRM strategies such as camp priorities in Idle mode and control of inter-RAT/inter-frequency handover in Active mode (see TS 23.501 [9]).

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per UE which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and a subscription parameter provided by the AMF to the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows.

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s
9.3.1.86 UE Security Capabilities - Section Description: This IE defines the supported algorithms for encryption and integrity protection in the UE.

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EEA0, "first bit" – 128-EEA1, "second bit" – 128-EEA2, "third bit" – 128-EEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EIA0, "first bit" – 128-EIA1, "second bit" – 128-EIA2, "third bit" – 128-EIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.

Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.74 UE Radio Capability - Section Description: This IE contains UE Radio Capability information. 9.3.1.74 UE Radio Capability IE Semantics: Includes either the RRC UERadioAccessCapabilityInformation message as defined in TS 38.331 [18], or the UERadioAccessCapabilityInformation-NB message as defined in 10.6.2 of TS 36.331 [21].
ENUMERATED (no further data, further data exists, …)
9.3.3.32 End Indication - Section Description: This IE indicates that there are no further NAS PDUs to be transmitted for this UE.
9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].
9.2.2.11 Allowed NSSAI IE Semantics: Indicates the S-NSSAIs permitted by the network 9.3.1.31 Allowed NSSAI - Section Description: This IE contains the allowed NSSAI.
9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].
9.3.1.144 UE Differentiation Information - Section Description: This IE is generated by the AMF based on the UE subscription information, it provides the Expected UE Behavior Information.
9.3.1.144 Periodic Communication Indicator IE Semantics: This IE indicates whether the UE communicates periodically or not, e.g. only on demand.
9.3.1.144 Periodic Time IE Semantics: This IE indicates the interval time of periodic communication, the unit is: second
9.3.1.144 Scheduled Communication Time IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time zone and day of the week when the UE is available for communication.

9.3.1.144 Day of Week IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a day of the week: first bit = Mon, second bit =Tue, third bit =Wed, and so on. Value ‘1’ indicates ‘scheduled. Value ‘0’ indicates ‘not scheduled’. If Day-Of-Week is not provided, this is interpreted as every day of the week.

9.3.1.144 Time of Day Start IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time to start of the day, each value represents the corresponding second since 00:00 of the day. If Time-Of-Day-Start is not provided, starting time is start of the day(s) indicated by Day-Of-Week-Mask.

9.3.1.144 Time of Day End IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time to start of the day, each value represents the corresponding second since 00:00 of the day. The value of this IE should be bigger than the value of Time of Day Start IE. If Time-Of-Day-End is not provided, ending time is end of the day(s) indicated by Day-Of-Week-Mask.
ENUMERATED (single packet, dual packets, multiple packets, …)

9.3.1.144 Traffic Profile IE Semantics: “single packet” indicates single packet transmission (UL or DL), “dual packets” indicates dual packet transmission (UL with subsequent DL, or DL with subsequent UL), “multiple packets” indicates multiple packets transmission.
ENUMERATED (battery powered, battery powered not rechargeable or replaceable, not battery powered, …)

9.3.1.144 Battery Indication IE Semantics: “battery powered” indicates that the UE is battery powered and the battery is rechargeable/replaceable, “battery powered not rechargeable or replaceable” indicates that the UE is battery powered but the battery is not rechargeable/replaceable, “not battery powered” indicates that the UE is not battery powered.

9.3.1.15 Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for e.g. RRC_INACTIVE configuration.
9.3.3.23 UE Identity Index Value - Section Description: This IE is used by the NG-RAN node to calculate the Paging Frame as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.3.23 Index Length 10 IE Semantics: Coded as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.1.90 Paging DRX - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging DRX as defined in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].

9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer - Section Description: This IE is used to assist NG-RAN to generate corresponding timer for periodic RNA update for RRC_INACTIVE UEs. 9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer IE Semantics: Bits 5 to 1 represent the binary coded timer value. Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.
9.3.1.23 MICO Mode Indication - Section Description: This IE indicates that the UE is configured with MICO mode by the AMF.
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.93 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: Included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.
9.3.1.154 Paging eDRX Information - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging eDRX parameters as defined in TS 36.304 [29].
ENUMERATED (hfhalf, hf1, hf2, hf4, hf6, hf8, hf10, hf12, hf14, hf16, hf32, hf64, hf128, hf256, …)
9.3.1.154 Paging eDRX Cycle IE Semantics: TeDRX defined in TS 36.304 [29]. Unit: [number of hyperframes].
9.3.1.154 Paging Time Window IE Semantics: Unit: [1.28 second].
9.3.1.86 UE Security Capabilities - Section Description: This IE defines the supported algorithms for encryption and integrity protection in the UE.

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EEA0, "first bit" – 128-EEA1, "second bit" – 128-EEA2, "third bit" – 128-EEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EIA0, "first bit" – 128-EIA1, "second bit" – 128-EIA2, "third bit" – 128-EIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.88 Security Context - Section Description: This IE provides security related parameters to the NG-RAN node which are used to derive security keys for user plane traffic and RRC signalling messages and for security parameter generation for subsequent mobility, see TS 33.501 [13].
9.3.1.88 Next Hop Chaining Count IE Semantics: Next Hop Chaining Counter (NCC) defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.88 Next-Hop NH IE Semantics: The NH together with the NCC is used to derive the security configuration as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key - Section Description: This IE is used to apply security in the NG-RAN for different scenarios as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key IE Semantics: Key material for NG-RAN node or Next Hop Key as defined in TS 33.501 [13]

9.2.3.4 NASC IE Semantics: Refers to either the “Intra N1 mode NAS transparent container” or the “S1 mode to N1 mode NAS transparent container”, the details of the IE definition and the encoding arespecified in TS 24.501 [26]. 9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU - Section Description: This IE contains a 5GC - UE or UE - 5GC message that is transferred without interpretation in the NG-RAN node. 9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU IE Semantics: The content is defined in TS 24.501 [26].

9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].
9.3.1.14 Trace Activation - Section Description: This IE defines parameters related to a trace session activation.

9.3.1.169 MDT Configuration-NR - Section Description: This IE defines the MDT configuration parameters of NR.

NG-RAN behaviour on receipt of this IE is specified in TS 23.216 [31]. 9.3.1.128 SRVCC Operation Possible IE Semantics: The value "Possible" indicates that UE and AMF are SRVCC capable.

9.3.1.129 IAB Authorized - Section Description: This IE provides information about the authorization status of the IAB node. 9.3.1.129 IAB Authorized IE Semantics: Indicates the IAB node authorization status.

9.3.1.140 Enhanced Coverage Restriction - Section Description: This IE provides information on the restriction information of using Coverage Enhancement. 9.3.1.140 Enhanced Coverage Restriction IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is restricted to use coverage enhancement. Value “restricted” indicates that the UE is not allowed to use coverage enhancement.
9.3.1.144 UE Differentiation Information - Section Description: This IE is generated by the AMF based on the UE subscription information, it provides the Expected UE Behavior Information.
9.3.1.144 Periodic Communication Indicator IE Semantics: This IE indicates whether the UE communicates periodically or not, e.g. only on demand.
9.3.1.144 Periodic Time IE Semantics: This IE indicates the interval time of periodic communication, the unit is: second
9.3.1.144 Scheduled Communication Time IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time zone and day of the week when the UE is available for communication.

9.3.1.144 Day of Week IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a day of the week: first bit = Mon, second bit =Tue, third bit =Wed, and so on. Value ‘1’ indicates ‘scheduled. Value ‘0’ indicates ‘not scheduled’. If Day-Of-Week is not provided, this is interpreted as every day of the week.

9.3.1.144 Time of Day Start IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time to start of the day, each value represents the corresponding second since 00:00 of the day. If Time-Of-Day-Start is not provided, starting time is start of the day(s) indicated by Day-Of-Week-Mask.

9.3.1.144 Time of Day End IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time to start of the day, each value represents the corresponding second since 00:00 of the day. The value of this IE should be bigger than the value of Time of Day Start IE. If Time-Of-Day-End is not provided, ending time is end of the day(s) indicated by Day-Of-Week-Mask.
ENUMERATED (single packet, dual packets, multiple packets, …)

9.3.1.144 Traffic Profile IE Semantics: “single packet” indicates single packet transmission (UL or DL), “dual packets” indicates dual packet transmission (UL with subsequent DL, or DL with subsequent UL), “multiple packets” indicates multiple packets transmission.

9.3.1.144 Battery Indication IE Semantics: “battery powered” indicates that the UE is battery powered and the battery is rechargeable/replaceable, “battery powered not rechargeable or replaceable” indicates that the UE is battery powered but the battery is not rechargeable/replaceable, “not battery powered” indicates that the UE is not battery powered.

9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.

Note: The Pre-emption Capability indicator applies to the allocation of resources for a QoS flow and as such it provides the trigger to the pre-emption procedures/processes of the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.19 Pre-emption Vulnerability IE Semantics: Desc.: This IE indicates the vulnerability of the QoS flow to pre-emption of other QoS flows (see TS 23.501 [9]). section_list.name: HANDOVER COMMAND
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to inform the source NG-RAN node that resources for the handover have been prepared at the target side.
Direction: AMF? NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.22 Handover Type - Section Description: This IE indicates which kind of handover was triggered in the source side. 9.3.1.22 Handover Type IE Semantics: Intra5GS: NG-RAN node to NG-RAN node 5GStoEPS: NG-RAN node to eNB EPSto5GS: eNB to NG-RAN node 5GStoUTRA: NG-RAN node to UTRA

9.2.3.2 - NAS Security Parameters from NG-RAN IE - iftoEPSUTRA: This IE shall be present if the Handover Type IE is set to the value "5GStoEPS" or "5GtoUTRA". 9.3.3.26 NAS Security Parameters from NG-RAN - Section Description: This IE provides security related parameters for inter-system handover from NG-RAN to E-UTRAN or from NG-RAN to UTRAN via the eNB to the UE. 9.3.3.26 NAS Security Parameters from NG-RAN IE Semantics: Refers to the N1 mode to S1 mode NAS transparent container IE, the details of the IE definition and the encoding are specified in TS 24.501 [26].
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.2.3.2 Handover Command Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Handover Command Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.10.
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.2.3.2 Handover Preparation Unsuccessful Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Handover Preparation Unsuccessful Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.18.

9.3.1.21 Target to Source Transparent Container - Section Description: This IE is used to transparently pass radio related information from the handover target to the handover source through the core network; it is produced by the target RAN node and is transmitted to the source RAN node. 9.3.1.21 Target to Source Transparent Container IE Semantics: This IE includes a transparent container from the target RAN node to the source RAN node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to the specifications of the target system. Note: In the current version of the specification, this IE may carry either the Target NG-RAN Node to Source NG-RAN Node Transparent Container IE or the Target eNB to Source eNB Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 36.413 [16], or the Target RNC to Source RNC Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 25.413 [28].

9.3.1.3 Criticality Diagnostics - Section Description: The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to the specifications of the target system. aoa:

Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].

9.3.1.22 Handover Type - Section Description: This IE indicates which kind of handover was triggered in the source side. 9.3.1.22 Handover Type IE Semantics: Intra5GS: NG-RAN node to NG-RAN node 5GStoEPS: NG-RAN node to eNB EPSto5GS: eNB to NG-RAN node 5GStoUTRA: NG-RAN node to UTRA

ENUMERATED (Control processing overload, Not enough user plane processing resources, Hardware failure, O&M intervention, Unknown PLMN, Unspecified, …)

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per UE which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and a subscription parameter provided by the AMF to the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows.

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s
├─Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE
9.3.1.15 Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for e.g. RRC_INACTIVE configuration.
9.3.3.23 UE Identity Index Value - Section Description: This IE is used by the NG-RAN node to calculate the Paging Frame as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.3.23 Index Length 10 IE Semantics: Coded as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.1.90 Paging DRX - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging DRX as defined in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].

9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer - Section Description: This IE is used to assist NG-RAN to generate corresponding timer for periodic RNA update for RRC_INACTIVE UEs. 9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer IE Semantics: Bits 5 to 1 represent the binary coded timer value. Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.
9.3.1.23 MICO Mode Indication - Section Description: This IE indicates that the UE is configured with MICO mode by the AMF.
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.93 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: Included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.
9.3.1.154 Paging eDRX Information - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging eDRX parameters as defined in TS 36.304 [29].
ENUMERATED (hfhalf, hf1, hf2, hf4, hf6, hf8, hf10, hf12, hf14, hf16, hf32, hf64, hf128, hf256, …)
9.3.1.154 Paging eDRX Cycle IE Semantics: TeDRX defined in TS 36.304 [29]. Unit: [number of hyperframes].
9.3.1.154 Paging Time Window IE Semantics: Unit: [1.28 second].
9.3.1.86 UE Security Capabilities - Section Description: This IE defines the supported algorithms for encryption and integrity protection in the UE.

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EEA0, "first bit" – 128-EEA1, "second bit" – 128-EEA2, "third bit" – 128-EEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EIA0, "first bit" – 128-EIA1, "second bit" – 128-EIA2, "third bit" – 128-EIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.88 Security Context - Section Description: This IE provides security related parameters to the NG-RAN node which are used to derive security keys for user plane traffic and RRC signalling messages and for security parameter generation for subsequent mobility, see TS 33.501 [13].
9.3.1.88 Next Hop Chaining Count IE Semantics: Next Hop Chaining Counter (NCC) defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.88 Next-Hop NH IE Semantics: The NH together with the NCC is used to derive the security configuration as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key - Section Description: This IE is used to apply security in the NG-RAN for different scenarios as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key IE Semantics: Key material for NG-RAN node or Next Hop Key as defined in TS 33.501 [13]

section_list.name: PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE
aoa:

Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.88 Security Context - Section Description: This IE provides security related parameters to the NG-RAN node which are used to derive security keys for user plane traffic and RRC signalling messages and for security parameter generation for subsequent mobility, see TS 33.501 [13].
9.3.1.88 Next Hop Chaining Count IE Semantics: Next Hop Chaining Counter (NCC) defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.88 Next-Hop NH IE Semantics: The NH together with the NCC is used to derive the security configuration as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key - Section Description: This IE is used to apply security in the NG-RAN for different scenarios as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key IE Semantics: Key material for NG-RAN node or Next Hop Key as defined in TS 33.501 [13]

9.3.1.55 New Security Context Indicator - Section Description: This IE indicates that the AMF has activated a new 5G NAS security context as described in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.55 New Security Context Indicator IE Semantics: The NSCI as defined in TS 33.501 [13].
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.2.3.9 Path Switch Request Acknowledge Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Path Switch Request Acknowledge Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.9.
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.2.3.9 Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.20.
9.2.3.9 Allowed NSSAI IE Semantics: Indicates the S-NSSAIs permitted by the network. 9.3.1.31 Allowed NSSAI - Section Description: This IE contains the allowed NSSAI.

9.3.1.15 Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for e.g. RRC_INACTIVE configuration.
9.3.3.23 UE Identity Index Value - Section Description: This IE is used by the NG-RAN node to calculate the Paging Frame as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.3.23 Index Length 10 IE Semantics: Coded as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.1.90 Paging DRX - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging DRX as defined in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].

9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer - Section Description: This IE is used to assist NG-RAN to generate corresponding timer for periodic RNA update for RRC_INACTIVE UEs. 9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer IE Semantics: Bits 5 to 1 represent the binary coded timer value. Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.
9.3.1.23 MICO Mode Indication - Section Description: This IE indicates that the UE is configured with MICO mode by the AMF.
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.93 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: Included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.
9.3.1.154 Paging eDRX Information - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging eDRX parameters as defined in TS 36.304 [29].
ENUMERATED (hfhalf, hf1, hf2, hf4, hf6, hf8, hf10, hf12, hf14, hf16, hf32, hf64, hf128, hf256, …)
9.3.1.154 Paging eDRX Cycle IE Semantics: TeDRX defined in TS 36.304 [29]. Unit: [number of hyperframes].
9.3.1.154 Paging Time Window IE Semantics: Unit: [1.28 second].
ENUMERATED (Subsequent state transition report, Single RRC connected state report, Cancel report, …)

9.3.1.91 RRC Inactive Transition Report Request - Section Description: This IE is used to request the NG-RAN node to report or stop reporting to the 5GC when the UE enters or leaves RRC_INACTIVE state.

9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.
9.3.1.116 Redirection for Voice EPS Fallback - Section Description: This IE is used to indicate that the AMF and the UE support the redirection for voice for EPS Fallback.
9.3.1.119 CN Assisted RAN Parameters Tuning - Section Description: This IE provides information for assisting in parameters tuning of the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.119 Expected UE Behaviour IE Semantics: This IE may be present in case the Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE IE is not included and is ignored otherwise. 9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).

ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

NG-RAN behaviour on receipt of this IE is specified in TS 23.216 [31]. 9.3.1.128 SRVCC Operation Possible IE Semantics: The value "Possible" indicates that UE and AMF are SRVCC capable.

9.3.1.140 Enhanced Coverage Restriction - Section Description: This IE provides information on the restriction information of using Coverage Enhancement. 9.3.1.140 Enhanced Coverage Restriction IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is restricted to use coverage enhancement. Value “restricted” indicates that the UE is not allowed to use coverage enhancement.

9.3.3.31 Extended Connected Time - Section Description: This IE indicates the minimum time the RAN should keep the UE in RRC_CONNECTED state regardless of inactivity, as defined in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.3.31 Extended Connected Time IE Semantics: Minimum time the RAN should keep the UE in RRC_CONNECTED state. Unit is second.
9.3.1.144 UE Differentiation Information - Section Description: This IE is generated by the AMF based on the UE subscription information, it provides the Expected UE Behavior Information.
9.3.1.144 Periodic Communication Indicator IE Semantics: This IE indicates whether the UE communicates periodically or not, e.g. only on demand.
9.3.1.144 Periodic Time IE Semantics: This IE indicates the interval time of periodic communication, the unit is: second
9.3.1.144 Scheduled Communication Time IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time zone and day of the week when the UE is available for communication.

9.3.1.144 Day of Week IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a day of the week: first bit = Mon, second bit =Tue, third bit =Wed, and so on. Value ‘1’ indicates ‘scheduled. Value ‘0’ indicates ‘not scheduled’. If Day-Of-Week is not provided, this is interpreted as every day of the week.

9.3.1.144 Time of Day Start IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time to start of the day, each value represents the corresponding second since 00:00 of the day. If Time-Of-Day-Start is not provided, starting time is start of the day(s) indicated by Day-Of-Week-Mask.

9.3.1.144 Time of Day End IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time to start of the day, each value represents the corresponding second since 00:00 of the day. The value of this IE should be bigger than the value of Time of Day Start IE. If Time-Of-Day-End is not provided, ending time is end of the day(s) indicated by Day-Of-Week-Mask.

section_list.name: PATH SWITCH REQUEST FAILURE
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to inform the NG-RAN node that a failure has occurred in the 5GC during the Path Switch Request procedure.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.2.3.10 Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the PDU session Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.20.

9.3.1.3 Criticality Diagnostics - Section Description: The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

section_list.name: HANDOVER CANCEL
aoa:

9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.2 Cause - Section Description: The purpose of the Cause IE is to indicate the reason for a particular event for the NGAP protocol.

ENUMERATED (Unspecified, TXnRELOCOverall expiry, Successful handover, Release due to NG-RAN generated reason, Release due to 5GC generated reason, Handover cancelled, Partial handover, Handover failure in target 5GC/NG-RAN node or target system, Handover target not allowed, TNGRELOCoverall expiry, TNGRELOCprep expiry, Cell not available, Unknown target ID, No radio resources available in target cell, Unknown local UE NGAP ID, Inconsistent remote UE NGAP ID, Handover desirable for radio reasons, Time critical handover, Resource optimisation handover, Reduce load in serving cell, User inactivity, Radio connection with UE lost, Radio resources not available, Invalid QoS combination, Failure in the radio interface procedure, Interaction with other procedure, Unknown PDU Session ID, Unknown QoS Flow ID, Multiple PDU Session ID Instances, Multiple QoS Flow ID Instances, Encryption and/or integrity protection algorithms not supported, NG intra-system handover triggered, NG inter-system handover triggered, Xn handover triggered, Not supported 5QI value, UE context transfer, IMS voice EPS fallback or RAT fallback triggered, UP integrity protection not possible, UP confidentiality protection not possible, Slice (s) not supported, UE in RRC_INACTIVE state not reachable, Redirection, Resources not available for the slice (s), UE maximum integrity protected data rate reason, Release due to CN-detected mobility, …, N26 interface not available, Release due to pre-emption, Multiple Location Reporting Reference ID Instances, RSN not available for the UP, NPN access denied, CAG only access denied)
