section_list.name: UPLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER
aoa:
This message is sent by the source NG-RAN node to transfer the uplink PDCP-SN and HFN receiver status and the downlink PDCP SN and HFN transmitter status during intra 5GC NG-based handover.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.108 RAN Status Transfer Transparent Container - Section Description: This IE is produced by the source NG-RAN node and is transmitted to the target NG-RAN node. It is used for intra 5GC NG handover. This IE is transparent to the AMF.
9.3.1.53 DRB ID - Section Description: This IE contains the DRB ID.

9.3.1.108 UL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN of the first missing UL PDCP SDU in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.108 Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE Semantics: The IE is used in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. The first bit indicates the status of the SDU after the First Missing UL PDCP SDU. The Nth bit indicates the status of the UL PDCP SDU in position (N + First Missing SDU Number) modulo (1 + the maximum value of the PDCP-SN). 0: PDCP SDU has not been received. 1: PDCP SDU has been received correctly.

9.3.1.108 UL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN of the first missing UL PDCP SDU in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.108 Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE Semantics: The IE is used in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. The first bit indicates the status of the SDU after the First Missing UL PDCP SDU. The Nth bit indicates the status of the UL PDCP SDU in position (N + First Missing SDU Number) modulo (1 + the maximum value of the PDCP-SN). 0: PDCP SDU has not been received. 1: PDCP SDU has been received correctly.

9.3.1.108 DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN that the target NG-RAN node should assign for the next DL PDCP SDU not having an SN yet in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.108 DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN that the target NG-RAN node should assign for the next DL PDCP SDU not having an SN yet in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN.
└─Old Associated QoS Flow List - UL End Marker Expected

9.3.1.108 Old Associated QoS Flow List - UL End Marker Expected IE Semantics: Indicates that the source NG-RAN node has initiated QoS flow re-mapping and has not yet received SDAP end markers, as described in TS 38.300 [8]. 9.3.1.99 Associated QoS Flow List - Section Description: This IE indicates the list of QoS flows associated with e.g. a DRB or UP TNL endpoint.
9.3.1.51 QoS Flow Identifier - Section Description: This IE identifies a QoS flow within a PDU Session. The definition and use of the QoS Flow Identifier is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.99 Current QoS Parameters Set Index IE Semantics: Index to the currently fulfilled alternative QoS parameters set 9.3.1.152 Alternative QoS Parameters Set Index - Section Description: This IE indicates the QoS parameters set which can currently be fulfilled. 9.3.1.152 Alternative QoS Parameters Set Index IE Semantics: Indicates the index of the item within the the Alternative QoS Parameters Set List IE corresponding to the currently fulfilled alternative QoS parameters set.

section_list.name: DOWNLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to the target NG-RAN node to transfer the uplink PDCP-SN and HFN receiver status and the downlink PDCP SN and HFN transmitter status during intra 5GC NG-based handover.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.108 RAN Status Transfer Transparent Container - Section Description: This IE is produced by the source NG-RAN node and is transmitted to the target NG-RAN node. It is used for intra 5GC NG handover. This IE is transparent to the AMF.
9.3.1.53 DRB ID - Section Description: This IE contains the DRB ID.

9.3.1.108 UL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN of the first missing UL PDCP SDU in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.108 Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE Semantics: The IE is used in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. The first bit indicates the status of the SDU after the First Missing UL PDCP SDU. The Nth bit indicates the status of the UL PDCP SDU in position (N + First Missing SDU Number) modulo (1 + the maximum value of the PDCP-SN). 0: PDCP SDU has not been received. 1: PDCP SDU has been received correctly.

9.3.1.108 UL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN of the first missing UL PDCP SDU in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.108 Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE Semantics: The IE is used in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. The first bit indicates the status of the SDU after the First Missing UL PDCP SDU. The Nth bit indicates the status of the UL PDCP SDU in position (N + First Missing SDU Number) modulo (1 + the maximum value of the PDCP-SN). 0: PDCP SDU has not been received. 1: PDCP SDU has been received correctly.

9.3.1.108 DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN that the target NG-RAN node should assign for the next DL PDCP SDU not having an SN yet in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.108 DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN that the target NG-RAN node should assign for the next DL PDCP SDU not having an SN yet in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN.
└─Old Associated QoS Flow List - UL End Marker Expected

9.3.1.108 Old Associated QoS Flow List - UL End Marker Expected IE Semantics: Indicates that the source NG-RAN node has initiated QoS flow re-mapping and has not yet received SDAP end markers, as described in TS 38.300 [8]. 9.3.1.99 Associated QoS Flow List - Section Description: This IE indicates the list of QoS flows associated with e.g. a DRB or UP TNL endpoint.
9.3.1.51 QoS Flow Identifier - Section Description: This IE identifies a QoS flow within a PDU Session. The definition and use of the QoS Flow Identifier is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.99 Current QoS Parameters Set Index IE Semantics: Index to the currently fulfilled alternative QoS parameters set 9.3.1.152 Alternative QoS Parameters Set Index - Section Description: This IE indicates the QoS parameters set which can currently be fulfilled. 9.3.1.152 Alternative QoS Parameters Set Index IE Semantics: Indicates the index of the item within the the Alternative QoS Parameters Set List IE corresponding to the currently fulfilled alternative QoS parameters set.

section_list.name: HANDOVER SUCCESS
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to the source NG-RAN node to indicate the successful access of the UE toward the target NG-RAN node.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

section_list.name: UPLINK RAN EARLY STATUS TRANSFER
aoa:
This message is sent by the source NG-RAN node to transfer the COUNT value(s) of the first forwarded downlink SDU(s) during NG DAPS Handover.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.190 Early Status Transfer Transparent Container - Section Description: The Early Status Transfer Transparent Container IE is an information element that is produced by the source NG-RAN node and is transmitted to the target NG-RAN node. This IE is used for the NG DAPS handover case. This IE is transparent to the 5GC.
└─DRBs Subject To Early Status Transfer List
└─DRBs Subject To Early Status Transfer Item
9.3.1.53 DRB ID - Section Description: This IE contains the DRB ID.

9.3.1.190 FIRST DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and Hyper frame number of the first DL SDU that the source NG-RAN node forwards to the target NG-RAN node in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.190 FIRST DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and Hyper frame number of the first DL SDU that the source NG-RAN node forwards to the target NG-RAN node in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN.

aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to transfer the COUNT value(s) of the first forwarded downlink SDU(s) during NG DAPS Handover.

9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

This IE is used for the NG DAPS handover case. This IE is transparent to the 5GC.
└─DRBs Subject To Early Status Transfer List
└─DRBs Subject To Early Status Transfer Item
9.3.1.53 DRB ID - Section Description: This IE contains the DRB ID.

9.3.1.190 FIRST DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and Hyper frame number of the first DL SDU that the source NG-RAN node forwards to the target NG-RAN node in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.190 FIRST DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and Hyper frame number of the first DL SDU that the source NG-RAN node forwards to the target NG-RAN node in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN.

section_list.name: PAGING
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF and is used to page a UE in one or several tracking areas.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.18 UE Paging Identity - Section Description: This IE represents the Identity with which the UE is paged.
9.3.3.20 5G-S-TMSI - Section Description: This IE is used for security reasons, to hide the identity of a subscriber.
9.3.3.12 AMF Set ID - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an AMF Set within the AMF Region.
9.3.3.19 AMF Pointer - Section Description: This IE is used to identify one or more AMF(s) within the AMF Set.
9.3.3.20 5G-TMSI IE Semantics: 5G-TMSI is unique within the AMF that allocated it.
9.3.1.90 Paging DRX - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging DRX as defined in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.
ENUMERATED (PrioLevel1, PrioLevel2, PrioLevel3, PrioLevel4, PrioLevel5, PrioLevel6, PrioLevel7, PrioLevel8, …)
9.3.1.78 Paging Priority - Section Description: This element indicates the paging priority for paging a UE. 9.3.1.78 Paging Priority IE Semantics: Lower value codepoint indicates higher priority.
9.3.1.68 UE Radio Capability for Paging - Section Description: This IE contains paging specific UE Radio Capability information.
│  ├─UE Radio Capability for Paging of NR
9.3.1.68 UE Radio Capability for Paging of NR IE Semantics: Includes the RRC UERadioPagingInformation message as defined in TS 38.331 [18].
│  ├─UE Radio Capability for Paging of E-UTRA
9.3.1.68 UE Radio Capability for Paging of E-UTRA IE Semantics: Includes the RRC UERadioPagingInformation message as defined in TS 36.331 [21].
│  └─UE Radio Capability for Paging of NB-IoT
9.3.1.68 UE Radio Capability for Paging of NB-IoT IE Semantics: Includes the RRC UERadioPagingInformation-NB message as defined in TS 36.331 [21].
9.3.3.22 Paging Origin - Section Description: This IE indicates whether Paging is originated due to the PDU sessions from the non-3GPP access.
9.3.1.69 Assistance Data for Paging - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for paging optimisation.
9.3.1.70 Assistance Data for Recommended Cells - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for paging in recommended cells.
9.3.1.71 Recommended Cells for Paging - Section Description: This IE contains the recommended cells for paging. This IE is transparent to the 5GC.

9.3.1.71 Recommended Cell Item IE Semantics: Includes visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.71 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: This is included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.
9.3.1.72 Paging Attempt Information - Section Description: This IE includes information related to the paging count over NG.
9.3.1.72 Paging Attempt Count IE Semantics: Paging attempt count (see TS 38.300 [8]).
9.3.1.72 Intended Number of Paging Attempts IE Semantics: Intended number of paging attempts (see TS 38.300 [8]).
9.3.1.72 Next Paging Area Scope IE Semantics: Indicates whether the paging area scope will change or not at next paging attempt. Usage specified in TS 38.300 [8].
9.3.1.183 NPN Paging Assistance Information - Section Description: This IE contains NPN Paging Assistance Information.

9.3.3.45 Allowed PNI-NPN List - Section Description: This IE contains information on allowed UE mobility in PNI-NPN including allowed PNI-NPNs and whether the UE is allowed to access non-CAG cells for each PLMN.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.45 PNI-NPN Restricted IE Semantics: If set to “restricted”, indicates that the UE is not allowed to access non-CAG cells for this PLMN.
9.3.3.43 CAG ID - Section Description: This IE is used to identify (together with a PLMN identifier) a Public Network Integrated NPN. 9.3.3.43 CAG ID IE Semantics: Defined in TS 23.003 [23].
│  └─Paging Assistance Data for CE Capable UE
9.3.1.141 Paging Assistance Data for CE Capable UE - Section Description: This IE provides Assistance Data for paging CE capable UE.
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.141 Coverage Enhancement Level IE Semantics: Includes either the UEPagingCoverageInformation message as defined in 10.2.2 of TS 36.331 [21], or the UEPagingCoverageInformation-NB message as defined in 10.6.2 of TS 36.331 [21].
9.3.1.138 NB-IoT Paging eDRX Information - Section Description: This IE indicates the NB-IoT Paging eDRX parameters as defined in TS 36.304 [29].
ENUMERATED (hf2, hf4, hf6, hf8, hf10, hf12, hf14, hf16, hf32, hf64, hf128, hf256, hf512, hf1024, …)
9.3.1.138 NB-IoT Paging eDRX Cycle IE Semantics: TeDRX defined in TS 36.304 [29]. Unit: [number of hyperframes].
9.3.1.138 NB-IoT Paging Time Window IE Semantics: Unit: [2.56 seconds]

9.2.4.1 NB-IoT Paging DRX IE Semantics: If this IE is present, the Paging DRX IE is ignored. 9.3.1.139 NB-IoT Paging DRX - Section Description: This IE indicates the NB-IoT UE specific Paging DRX as defined in TS 36.304 [29]. 9.3.1.139 NB-IoT Paging DRX IE Semantics: Unit: [number of radioframes]

9.3.1.140 Enhanced Coverage Restriction - Section Description: This IE provides information on the restriction information of using Coverage Enhancement. 9.3.1.140 Enhanced Coverage Restriction IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is restricted to use coverage enhancement. Value “restricted” indicates that the UE is not allowed to use coverage enhancement.

9.3.1.143 WUS Assistance Information - Section Description: This IE provides WUS Assistance Information to be used by the NG-RAN node for determining the WUS group for the UE. 9.3.1.143 Paging Probability Information IE Semantics: Unit: percentage
9.3.1.154 Paging eDRX Information - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging eDRX parameters as defined in TS 36.304 [29].
ENUMERATED (hfhalf, hf1, hf2, hf4, hf6, hf8, hf10, hf12, hf14, hf16, hf32, hf64, hf128, hf256, …)
9.3.1.154 Paging eDRX Cycle IE Semantics: TeDRX defined in TS 36.304 [29]. Unit: [number of hyperframes].
9.3.1.154 Paging Time Window IE Semantics: Unit: [1.28 second].

9.3.1.155 CE-mode-B Restricted - Section Description: This IE provides information on the restriction information of using Coverage Enhancement Mode B. 9.3.1.155 CE-mode-B Restricted IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is restricted to use coverage enhancement. Value “restricted” indicates that the UE is not allowed to use coverage enhancement mode B. Value “not-restricted” indicates that the UE is allowed to use coverage enhancement mode B.

section_list.name: INITIAL UE MESSAGE

Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF

CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU - Section Description: This IE contains a 5GC - UE or UE - 5GC message that is transferred without interpretation in the NG-RAN node. 9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU IE Semantics: The content is defined in TS 24.501 [26].
9.3.1.16 User Location Information - Section Description: This IE is used to provide location information of the UE.
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).

9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.16 IP Address IE Semantics: UE's local IP address used to reach the N3IWF 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. 9.3.1.16 Port Number IE Semantics: UDP or TCP source port number if NAT is detected.
9.3.1.16 TNAP ID IE Semantics: TNAP Identifier used to identify the TNAP. Details in TS 29.571 [35].

9.3.1.16 IP Address IE Semantics: UE's local IP address used to reach the TNGF. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].
9.3.1.16 Port Number IE Semantics: UDP or TCP source port number if NAT is detected.
9.3.1.16 TWAP ID IE Semantics: TWAP Identifier used to identify the TWAP. Details in TS 29.571 [35].

9.3.1.16 IP Address IE Semantics: Non-5G-Capable over WLAN device's local IP address used to reach the TWIF. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].
9.3.1.16 Port Number IE Semantics: UDP or TCP source port number if NAT is detected.
9.3.1.16 W-AGF user location information IE Semantics: Indicates the location information via wireline access as specified in TS 23.316 [34].
9.3.1.164 W-AGF User Location Information - Section Description: This IE indicates the location information via wireline access as specified in TS 23.316 [34].
9.3.1.164 Global Line ID IE Semantics: Encoded as defined in TS 23.003 [23].
9.3.1.164 HFC Node ID IE Semantics: Indicates the identifier of the HFC node as specified in [37]. Encoded as defined in TS 23.003 [23].
ENUMERATED (emergency, highPriorityAccess, mt-Access, mo-Signalling, mo-Data, mo-VoiceCall, mo-VideoCall, mo-SMS, mps-PriorityAccess, mcs-PriorityAccess, …, notAvailable, mo-ExceptionData)

9.3.1.111 RRC Establishment Cause - Section Description: This IE indicates the reason for RRC Connection Establishment as received from the UE in the EstablishmentCause defined in TS 38.331 [18] and TS 36.331 [21], or the reason for RRC Connection Resume as received from the UE in the ResumeCause defined in TS 38.331 [18] and TS 36.331 [21], or the reason for RRC Connection Establishment as received from the UE in the EstablishmentCause-NB defined in TS 36.331 [21]. 9.3.1.111 RRC Establishment Cause IE Semantics: The notAvailable value is used in case the UE is re-establishing an RRC connection but there is fallback to RRC connection establishment as described in [18], or the ResumceCause received from the UE does not map to any other value of the RRC Establishment Cause IE.
9.3.3.20 5G-S-TMSI - Section Description: This IE is used for security reasons, to hide the identity of a subscriber.
9.3.3.12 AMF Set ID - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an AMF Set within the AMF Region.
9.3.3.19 AMF Pointer - Section Description: This IE is used to identify one or more AMF(s) within the AMF Set.
9.3.3.20 5G-TMSI IE Semantics: 5G-TMSI is unique within the AMF that allocated it.
9.3.3.12 AMF Set ID - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an AMF Set within the AMF Region.
9.3.1.31 Allowed NSSAI - Section Description: This IE contains the allowed NSSAI.
9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].

9.3.3.27 Source to Target AMF Information Reroute - Section Description: This IE is used to transparently pass information provided by NSSF from the source AMF to the target AMF through the NG-RAN node; it is produced by the source core network node and is transmitted to the target core network node.

9.3.3.27 Configured NSSAI IE Semantics: The maximum number of S-NSSAI in Configured NSSAI is 16.This IE contains optional mapping S-NSSAI. When present, this IE shall be transmitted transparent from the source Core network node to the target Core network node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to description in TS 29.531 [30]

9.3.3.27 Rejected NSSAI in PLMN IE Semantics: This IE contain the rejected NSSAI(s) in the PLMN. When present, this IE shall be transmitted transparent from the source Core network node to the target Core network node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to description in TS 29.531 [30].

9.3.3.27 Rejected NSSAI in TA IE Semantics: This IE contain the rejected NSSAI(s) in the TA. When present, this IE shall be transmitted transparent from the source Core network node to the target Core network node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to description in TS 29.531 [30].

9.2.5.1 Selected PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Indicates the selected PLMN id for the non-3GPP access. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.2.5.1 IAB Node Indication IE Semantics: Indication of an IAB node
9.3.1.156 CE-mode-B Support Indicator - Section Description: This IE indicates whether CE-mode-B as specified in TS 36.306[42] is supported for the UE.
9.3.1.157 LTE-M Indication - Section Description: This IE is provided by the NG-RAN node to inform that the UE indicates category M1 or M2 in its UE Radio Capability.
9.2.5.1 Authenticated Indication IE Semantics: Indicates the FN-RG has been authenticated by the access network.
9.3.3.46 NPN Access Information - Section Description: This IE contains information to perform access control for NPN.
9.3.3.47 Cell CAG List - Section Description: This IE indicates the list of CAG IDs supported by a cell.
9.3.3.43 CAG ID - Section Description: This IE is used to identify (together with a PLMN identifier) a Public Network Integrated NPN. 9.3.3.43 CAG ID IE Semantics: Defined in TS 23.003 [23].

aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF and is used for carrying NAS information over the NG interface.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.3.21 AMF Name - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify the AMF (see TS 38.300 [8]). It may also be used as a human readable name of the AMF.

9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority - Section Description: This IE contains the service priority as defined in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority IE Semantics: Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 256 as the lowest priority

9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU - Section Description: This IE contains a 5GC - UE or UE - 5GC message that is transferred without interpretation in the NG-RAN node. 9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU IE Semantics: The content is defined in TS 24.501 [26].

9.3.1.85 Mobility Restriction List - Section Description: This IE defines roaming or access restrictions for subsequent mobility action for which the NG-RAN provides information about the target of the mobility action towards the UE, e.g., handover, or for SCG selection during dual connectivity operation or for assigning proper RNAs. NG-RAN behaviour upon receiving this IE is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).

9.3.1.85 Equivalent PLMNs IE Semantics: Allowed PLMNs in addition to Serving PLMN. This list corresponds to the list of "equivalent PLMNs" as defined in TS 24.501 [26]. This list is part of the roaming restriction information. Roaming restrictions apply to PLMNs other than the Serving PLMN and Equivalent PLMNs.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.85 RAT Restrictions IE Semantics: This IE contains RAT restriction related information as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).

9.3.1.85 RAT Restriction Information IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a RAT. If a bit is set to "1", the respective RAT is restricted for the UE. If a bit is set to "0", the respective RAT is not restricted for the UE. Bits 3-7 reserved for future use.

9.3.1.85 Extended RAT Restriction Information IE Semantics: If this IE is included, the RAT Restriction Information IE is ignored. 9.3.1.126 Extended RAT Restriction Information - Section Description: This IE provides RAT restrictions as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.126 Primary RAT Restriction IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a RAT. If a bit is set to "1", the respective RAT is restricted for the UE. If a bit is set to "0", the respective RAT is not restricted for the UE. Bits 3-7 reserved for future use. The Primary RAT is the RAT used in the access cell, or target cell.
BIT STRING { e-UTRA (0), nR (1), e-UTRA-unlicensed (2), nR-unlicensed (3)} (SIZE (8, …))

9.3.1.126 Secondary RAT Restriction IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a RAT. If a bit is set to "1", the respective RAT is restricted for the UE. If a bit is set to "0", the respective RAT is not restricted for the UE. Bits 4-7 reserved for future use. A Secondary RAT is a RAT used in any cell serving the UE excluding the PCell.
9.3.1.85 Forbidden Area Information IE Semantics: This IE contains Forbidden Area information as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.85 TAC IE Semantics: The TAC of the forbidden TAI. 9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.
9.3.1.85 Service Area Information IE Semantics: This IE contains Service Area Restriction information as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.85 TAC IE Semantics: The TAC of the allowed TAI. 9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.
9.3.1.85 TAC IE Semantics: The TAC of the not-allowed TAI. 9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.85 Last E-UTRAN PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Indicates the E-UTRAN PLMN ID from where the UE formerly handed over to 5GS and which is preferred in case of subsequent mobility to EPS. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
│  ├─Core Network Type Restriction for Serving PLMN
9.3.1.85 Core Network Type Restriction for Serving PLMN IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is restricted to connect to EPC for the Serving PLMN as specified in TS 23.501 [9].
│  ├─Core Network Type Restriction for Equivalent PLMNs

9.3.1.85 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Includes any of the Equivalent PLMNs listed in the Mobility Restriction List IE for which CN Type restriction applies as specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.85 Core Network Type Restriction IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is restricted to connect to EPC or to 5GC for this PLMN.
9.3.1.184 NPN Mobility Information - Section Description: This IE indicates the access restrictions related to an NPN.
9.3.3.42 NID - Section Description: This IE is used to identify (together with a PLMN identifier) a Stand-alone Non-Public Network. 9.3.3.42 NID IE Semantics: Defined in TS 23.003 [23].

9.3.3.45 Allowed PNI-NPN List - Section Description: This IE contains information on allowed UE mobility in PNI-NPN including allowed PNI-NPNs and whether the UE is allowed to access non-CAG cells for each PLMN.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.45 PNI-NPN Restricted IE Semantics: If set to “restricted”, indicates that the UE is not allowed to access non-CAG cells for this PLMN.
9.3.3.43 CAG ID - Section Description: This IE is used to identify (together with a PLMN identifier) a Public Network Integrated NPN. 9.3.3.43 CAG ID IE Semantics: Defined in TS 23.003 [23].

9.3.1.61 Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority - Section Description: This IE is used to define local configuration for RRM strategies such as camp priorities in Idle mode and control of inter-RAT/inter-frequency handover in Active mode (see TS 23.501 [9]).

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per UE which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and a subscription parameter provided by the AMF to the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows.

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s
9.2.5.2 Allowed NSSAI IE Semantics: Indicates the S-NSSAIs permitted by the network. 9.3.1.31 Allowed NSSAI - Section Description: This IE contains the allowed NSSAI.
9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].

9.3.1.128 SRVCC Operation Possible - Section Description: This IE indicates that both UE and AMF are SRVCC-capable. NG-RAN behaviour on receipt of this IE is specified in TS 23.216 [31]. 9.3.1.128 SRVCC Operation Possible IE Semantics: The value "Possible" indicates that UE and AMF are SRVCC capable.

9.3.1.140 Enhanced Coverage Restriction - Section Description: This IE provides information on the restriction information of using Coverage Enhancement. 9.3.1.140 Enhanced Coverage Restriction IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is restricted to use coverage enhancement. Value “restricted” indicates that the UE is not allowed to use coverage enhancement.

9.3.3.31 Extended Connected Time - Section Description: This IE indicates the minimum time the RAN should keep the UE in RRC_CONNECTED state regardless of inactivity, as defined in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.3.31 Extended Connected Time IE Semantics: Minimum time the RAN should keep the UE in RRC_CONNECTED state. Unit is second.
9.3.1.144 UE Differentiation Information - Section Description: This IE is generated by the AMF based on the UE subscription information, it provides the Expected UE Behavior Information.
9.3.1.144 Periodic Communication Indicator IE Semantics: This IE indicates whether the UE communicates periodically or not, e.g. only on demand.
9.3.1.144 Periodic Time IE Semantics: This IE indicates the interval time of periodic communication, the unit is: second
9.3.1.144 Scheduled Communication Time IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time zone and day of the week when the UE is available for communication.

9.3.1.144 Day of Week IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a day of the week: first bit = Mon, second bit =Tue, third bit =Wed, and so on. Value ‘1’ indicates ‘scheduled. Value ‘0’ indicates ‘not scheduled’. If Day-Of-Week is not provided, this is interpreted as every day of the week.

9.3.1.144 Time of Day Start IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time to start of the day, each value represents the corresponding second since 00:00 of the day. If Time-Of-Day-Start is not provided, starting time is start of the day(s) indicated by Day-Of-Week-Mask.

9.3.1.144 Time of Day End IE Semantics: This IE indicates the time to start of the day, each value represents the corresponding second since 00:00 of the day. The value of this IE should be bigger than the value of Time of Day Start IE. If Time-Of-Day-End is not provided, ending time is end of the day(s) indicated by Day-Of-Week-Mask.
ENUMERATED (single packet, dual packets, multiple packets, …)

9.3.1.144 Traffic Profile IE Semantics: “single packet” indicates single packet transmission (UL or DL), “dual packets” indicates dual packet transmission (UL with subsequent DL, or DL with subsequent UL), “multiple packets” indicates multiple packets transmission.
ENUMERATED (battery powered, battery powered not rechargeable or replaceable, not battery powered, …)

9.3.1.144 Battery Indication IE Semantics: “battery powered” indicates that the UE is battery powered and the battery is rechargeable/replaceable, “battery powered not rechargeable or replaceable” indicates that the UE is battery powered but the battery is not rechargeable/replaceable, “not battery powered” indicates that the UE is not battery powered.

9.3.1.155 CE-mode-B Restricted - Section Description: This IE provides information on the restriction information of using Coverage Enhancement Mode B. 9.3.1.155 CE-mode-B Restricted IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is restricted to use coverage enhancement. Value “restricted” indicates that the UE is not allowed to use coverage enhancement mode B. Value “not-restricted” indicates that the UE is allowed to use coverage enhancement mode B.

9.3.1.74 UE Radio Capability - Section Description: This IE contains UE Radio Capability information. 9.3.1.74 UE Radio Capability IE Semantics: Includes either the RRC UERadioAccessCapabilityInformation message as defined in TS 38.331 [18], or the UERadioAccessCapabilityInformation-NB message as defined in 10.6.2 of TS 36.331 [21].
9.3.1.192 UE Capability Info Request - Section Description: This IE indicates the request to provide to the AMF the UE radio capability related information when retrieved from the UE.
ENUMERATED (no further data, further data exists, …)
9.3.3.32 End Indication - Section Description: This IE indicates that there are no further NAS PDUs to be transmitted for this UE.
9.3.1.142 UE Radio Capability ID - Section Description: This IE contains the UE Radio Capability ID. 9.3.1.142 UE Radio Capability ID IE Semantics: Defined in 23.003 [23].

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EEA0, "first bit" – 128-EEA1, "second bit" – 128-EEA2, "third bit" – 128-EEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EIA0, "first bit" – 128-EIA1, "second bit" – 128-EIA2, "third bit" – 128-EIA3, other bits reserved for future use. 9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

section_list.name: TRACE START
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to initiate a trace session for a UE.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.14 Trace Activation - Section Description: This IE defines parameters related to a trace session activation.

9.3.1.14 NG-RAN Trace ID IE Semantics: This IE is composed of the following: Trace Reference defined in TS 32.422 [11] (leftmost 6 octets, with PLMN information encoded as in 9.3.3.1), and Trace Recording Session Reference defined in TS 32.422 [11] (last 2 octets).

9.3.1.14 Interfaces to Trace IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an NG-RAN node interface: first bit = NG-C, second bit = Xn-C, third bit = Uu, fourth bit = F1-C, fifth bit = E1: other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates 'should be traced'. Value '0' indicates 'should not be traced'.
ENUMERATED (minimum, medium, maximum, minimumWithoutVendorSpecificExtension, mediumWithoutVendorSpecificExtension, maximumWithoutVendorSpecificExtension, …)
9.3.1.14 Trace Depth IE Semantics: Defined in TS 32.422 [11].

9.3.1.14 Trace Collection Entity IP Address IE Semantics: For File based Reporting. Defined in TS 32.422 [11]. This IE is ignored if the Trace Collection Entity URI IE is present. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].
9.3.1.167 MDT Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the MDT configuration parameters.
9.3.1.169 MDT Configuration-NR - Section Description: This IE defines the MDT configuration parameters of NR.
ENUMERATED (Immediate MDT only, Logged MDT only, Immediate MDT and Trace, …)
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.169 TAC IE Semantics: The TAI is derived using the current serving PLMN. 9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.169 Measurements to Activate IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap indicates a MDT measurement, as defined in TS 37.320 [41]. First Bit = M1, Second Bit= M2, Third Bit = M4, Fourth Bit = M5, Fifth Bit = M6, Sixth Bit = M7, Seventh Bit = logging of M1 from event triggered measurement reports according to existing RRM configuration, other bits reserved for future use. Value “1” indicates “activate” and value “0” indicates “do not activate”.

9.3.1.169 - M1 Configuration IE - ifM1: This IE shall be present if the Measurements to Activate IE has the first bit set to “1”. 9.3.1.171 M1 Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for M1 measurement collection.
9.3.1.171 - M1 Threshold Event A2 IE - ifM1A2trigger: This IE shall be present if the M1 Reporting Trigger IE is set to “A2event-triggered” or to “A2event-triggered periodic”.
9.3.1.171 Threshold RSRP IE Semantics: This IE is defined in TS 38.331 [18].
9.3.1.171 Threshold RSRQ IE Semantics: This IE is defined in TS 38.331 [18].
9.3.1.171 Threshold SINR IE Semantics: This IE is defined in TS 38.331 [18].
9.3.1.171 - M1 Periodic Reporting IE - ifperiodicMDT: This IE shall be present if the M1 Reporting Trigger IE is set to “periodic”, or to “A2event-triggered periodic”.
ENUMERATED (ms120, ms240, ms480, ms640, ms1024, ms2048, ms5120, ms10240, min1, min6, min12, min30, min60)
9.3.1.171 Report Interval IE Semantics: This IE is defined in TS 38.331 [18].
9.3.1.171 Report Amount IE Semantics: Number of reports.

9.3.1.169 - M4 Configuration IE - ifM4: This IE shall be present if the Measurements to Activate IE has the third bit set to “1”. 9.3.1.172 M4 Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for M4 measurement collection.

9.3.1.169 - M5 Configuration IE - ifM5: This IE shall be present if the Measurements to Activate IE has the fourth bit set to “1”. 9.3.1.173 M5 Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for M5 measurement collection.

9.3.1.169 - M6 Configuration IE - ifM6: This IE shall be present if the Measurements to Activate IE has the fitth bit set to “1”. 9.3.1.174 M6 Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for M6 measurement collection.
ENUMERATED (ms120, ms240, ms480, ms640, ms1024, ms2048, ms5120, ms10240, ms20480, ms40960, min1, min6, min12, min30, …)

9.3.1.169 - M7 Configuration IE - ifM7: This IE shall be present if the Measurements to Activate IE has the sixth bit set to “1”. 9.3.1.175 M7 Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for M7 measurement collection.
9.3.1.175 M7 Collection Period IE Semantics: Unit: minutes
9.3.1.177 Bluetooth Measurement Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for Bluetooth measurement collection.
9.3.1.177 BT RSSI IE Semantics: In case of Immediate MDT, it corresponds to M8 measurement as defined in TS 37.320 [41].
9.3.1.178 WLAN Measurement Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for WLAN measurement collection.
9.3.1.178 WLAN RSSI IE Semantics: In case of Immediate MDT, it corresponds to M8 as defined in TS 37.320 [41].
9.3.1.178 WLAN RTT IE Semantics: In case of Immediate MDT, it corresponds to M9 as defined in TS 37.320 [41].

9.3.1.176 MDT Location Information - Section Description: This IE defines the MDT Location Information. 9.3.1.176 MDT Location Information IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents requested location information as defined in TS 37.320 [41]. First Bit = GNSS Other bits are reserved for future use and are ignored if received. Value “1” indicates “activate” and value “0” indicates “do not activate”.
9.3.1.179 Sensor Measurement Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for Sensor measurement collection.
9.3.1.169 Logging interval IE Semantics: This IE is defined in TS 38.331 [18].
9.3.1.169 Logging duration IE Semantics: This IE is defined in TS 38.331 [18]. Unit: [minute].
9.3.1.180 Event Trigger Logged MDT Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the event trigger logged MDT configuration.
9.3.1.180 Threshold RSRP IE Semantics: This IE is defined in TS 38.331 [18].
9.3.1.180 Threshold RSRQ IE Semantics: This IE is defined in TS 38.331 [18].
9.3.1.180 Hysteresis IE Semantics: This parameter is used within the entry and leave condition of an event triggered reporting condition.
9.3.1.180 Time to Trigger IE Semantics: Time during which specific criteria for the event needs to be met in order to trigger a measurement report.
9.3.1.177 Bluetooth Measurement Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for Bluetooth measurement collection.
9.3.1.177 BT RSSI IE Semantics: In case of Immediate MDT, it corresponds to M8 measurement as defined in TS 37.320 [41].
9.3.1.178 WLAN Measurement Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for WLAN measurement collection.
9.3.1.178 WLAN RSSI IE Semantics: In case of Immediate MDT, it corresponds to M8 as defined in TS 37.320 [41].
9.3.1.178 WLAN RTT IE Semantics: In case of Immediate MDT, it corresponds to M9 as defined in TS 37.320 [41].
9.3.1.179 Sensor Measurement Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the parameters for Sensor measurement collection.
9.3.1.182 Area Scope of Neighbour Cells - Section Description: This IE defines the area scope of neighbour cells for logged MDT.
9.3.1.181 NR Frequency Info - Section Description: This defines the carrier frequency and bands used in a cell for a given direction (UL or DL) in FDD or for both UL and DL directions in TDD.

9.3.1.181 NR ARFCN IE Semantics: RF Reference Frequency as defined in TS 38.104 [39], section 5.4.2.1. The frequency provided in this IE identifies the absolute frequency position of the reference resource block (Common RB 0) of the carrier. Its lowest subcarrier is also known as Point A.
9.3.1.181 NR Frequency Band IE Semantics: Primary NR Operating Band as defined in TS 38.104 [39], section 5.4.2.3. The value 1 corresponds to n1, value 2 corresponds to NR operating band n2, etc.
9.3.1.182 NR PCI IE Semantics: NR Physical Cell ID
9.3.1.168 MDT PLMN List - Section Description: The purpose of the MDT PLMN List IE is to provide the list of PLMN allowed for MDT.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.170 MDT Configuration-EUTRA - Section Description: This IE defines the MDT configuration parameters of EUTRA.
ENUMERATED (Immediate MDT only, Logged MDT only, Immediate MDT and Trace, …)
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).
9.3.1.170 TAC IE Semantics: The TAI is derived using the current serving PLMN. 9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.
9.3.1.170 MDT Mode IE Semantics: MDTMode IE defined in TS 36.413 [16].
9.3.1.168 MDT PLMN List - Section Description: The purpose of the MDT PLMN List IE is to provide the list of PLMN allowed for MDT.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).

9.3.1.14 Trace Collection Entity URI IE Semantics: For Streaming based Reporting. Defined in TS 32.422 [11]. 9.3.2.14 URI - Section Description: This IE is an URI. 9.3.2.14 URI IE Semantics: String representing URI (Uniform Resource Identifier)

section_list.name: TRACE FAILURE INDICATION
aoa:
This message is sent by the NG-RAN node to indicate that a Trace Start procedure or a Deactivate Trace procedure has failed for a UE.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.2.10.2 NG-RAN Trace ID IE Semantics: As per NG-RAN Trace ID in Trace Activation IE
9.3.1.2 Cause - Section Description: The purpose of the Cause IE is to indicate the reason for a particular event for the NGAP protocol.

ENUMERATED (Unspecified, TXnRELOCOverall expiry, Successful handover, Release due to NG-RAN generated reason, Release due to 5GC generated reason, Handover cancelled, Partial handover, Handover failure in target 5GC/NG-RAN node or target system, Handover target not allowed, TNGRELOCoverall expiry, TNGRELOCprep expiry, Cell not available, Unknown target ID, No radio resources available in target cell, Unknown local UE NGAP ID, Inconsistent remote UE NGAP ID, Handover desirable for radio reasons, Time critical handover, Resource optimisation handover, Reduce load in serving cell, User inactivity, Radio connection with UE lost, Radio resources not available, Invalid QoS combination, Failure in the radio interface procedure, Interaction with other procedure, Unknown PDU Session ID, Unknown QoS Flow ID, Multiple PDU Session ID Instances, Multiple QoS Flow ID Instances, Encryption and/or integrity protection algorithms not supported, NG intra-system handover triggered, NG inter-system handover triggered, Xn handover triggered, Not supported 5QI value, UE context transfer, IMS voice EPS fallback or RAT fallback triggered, UP integrity protection not possible, UP confidentiality protection not possible, Slice (s) not supported, UE in RRC_INACTIVE state not reachable, Redirection, Resources not available for the slice (s), UE maximum integrity protected data rate reason, Release due to CN-detected mobility, …, N26 interface not available, Release due to pre-emption, Multiple Location Reporting Reference ID Instances, RSN not available for the UP, NPN access denied, CAG only access denied)
ENUMERATED (Normal release, Authentication failure, Deregister, Unspecified, …)

ENUMERATED (Transfer syntax error, Abstract syntax error (reject), Abstract syntax error (ignore and notify), Message not compatible with receiver state, Semantic error, Abstract syntax error (falsely constructed message), Unspecified, …)
ENUMERATED (Control processing overload, Not enough user plane processing resources, Hardware failure, O&M intervention, Unknown PLMN, Unspecified, …)

ENUMERATED (Unspecified, TXnRELOCOverall expiry, Successful handover, Release due to NG-RAN generated reason, Release due to 5GC generated reason, Handover cancelled, Partial handover, Handover failure in target 5GC/NG-RAN node or target system, Handover target not allowed, TNGRELOCoverall expiry, TNGRELOCprep expiry, Cell not available, Unknown target ID, No radio resources available in target cell, Unknown local UE NGAP ID, Inconsistent remote UE NGAP ID, Handover desirable for radio reasons, Time critical handover, Resource optimisation handover, Reduce load in serving cell, User inactivity, Radio connection with UE lost, Radio resources not available, Invalid QoS combination, Failure in the radio interface procedure, Interaction with other procedure, Unknown PDU Session ID, Unknown QoS Flow ID, Multiple PDU Session ID Instances, Multiple QoS Flow ID Instances, Encryption and/or integrity protection algorithms not supported, NG intra-system handover triggered, NG inter-system handover triggered, Xn handover triggered, Not supported 5QI value, UE context transfer, IMS voice EPS fallback or RAT fallback triggered, UP integrity protection not possible, UP confidentiality protection not possible, Slice (s) not supported, UE in RRC_INACTIVE state not reachable, Redirection, Resources not available for the slice (s), UE maximum integrity protected data rate reason, Release due to CN-detected mobility, …, N26 interface not available, Release due to pre-emption, Multiple Location Reporting Reference ID Instances, RSN not available for the UP, NPN access denied, CAG only access denied)
ENUMERATED (Normal release, Authentication failure, Deregister, Unspecified, …)

ENUMERATED (Transfer syntax error, Abstract syntax error (reject), Abstract syntax error (ignore and notify), Message not compatible with receiver state, Semantic error, Abstract syntax error (falsely constructed message), Unspecified, …)
ENUMERATED (Control processing overload, Not enough user plane processing resources, Hardware failure, O&M intervention, Unknown PLMN, Unspecified, …)

section_list.name: Criticality Diagnostics
aoa:
The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing.
For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

section_list.name: Bit Rate
aoa: 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL or by UE in sidelink within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. The unit is: bit/s

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.81 Packet Error Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the Packet Error Rate for a QoS flow.

section_list.name: QoS Flow Level QoS Parameters
aoa: This IE defines the QoS parameters to be applied to a QoS flow.
9.3.1.28 Non Dynamic 5QI Descriptor - Section Description: This IE indicates the QoS Characteristics for a standardized or pre-configured 5QI for downlink and uplink.
9.3.1.28 5QI IE Semantics: Indicates the standardized or pre-configured 5QI as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.28 Priority Level IE Semantics: Priority Level is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. When included, it overrides standardized or pre-configured value. 9.3.1.84 Priority Level - Section Description: This IE indicates the Priority Level for a QoS flow. 9.3.1.84 Priority Level IE Semantics: Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 127 as the lowest priority.

9.3.1.28 Averaging Window IE Semantics: Averaging Window is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. When included, it overrides standardized or pre-configured value. 9.3.1.82 Averaging Window - Section Description: This IE indicates the Averaging Window for a QoS flow, and applies to GBR QoS flows only. 9.3.1.82 Averaging Window IE Semantics: Unit: ms. The default value of the IE is 2000ms.

9.3.1.28 Maximum Data Burst Volume IE Semantics: Maximum Data Burst Volume is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.1.28 CN Packet Delay Budget Uplink IE Semantics: Core Network Packet Delay Budget is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.1.18 Dynamic 5QI Descriptor - Section Description: This IE indicates the QoS Characteristics for a Non-standardised or not pre-configured 5QI for downlink and uplink.

9.3.1.18 Priority Level IE Semantics: Priority Level is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.1.84 Priority Level - Section Description: This IE indicates the Priority Level for a QoS flow. 9.3.1.84 Priority Level IE Semantics: Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 127 as the lowest priority.

9.3.1.19 Allocation and Retention Priority - Section Description: This IE specifies the relative importance of a QoS flow compared to other QoS flows for allocation and retention of NG-RAN resources.

9.3.1.19 Priority Level IE Semantics: Desc.: This IE defines the relative importance of a resource request (see TS 23.501 [9]). Usage: Values are ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e., with 1 as the highest priority and 15 as the lowest priority.
ENUMERATED (shall not trigger pre-emption, may trigger pre-emption, …)

9.3.1.19 Pre-emption Capability IE Semantics: Desc.: This IE indicates the pre-emption capability of the request on other QoS flows (see TS 23.501 [9]). Usage: The QoS flow shall not pre-empt other QoS flows or, the QoS flow may pre-empt other QoS flows. Note: The Pre-emption Capability indicator applies to the allocation of resources for a QoS flow and as such it provides the trigger to the pre-emption procedures/processes of the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.19 Pre-emption Vulnerability IE Semantics: Desc.: This IE indicates the vulnerability of the QoS flow to pre-emption of other QoS flows (see TS 23.501 [9]). Usage: The QoS flow shall not be pre-empted by other QoS flows or the QoS flow may be pre-empted by other QoS flows. Note: The Pre-emption Vulnerability indicator applies for the entire duration of the QoS flow, unless modified and as such indicates whether the QoS flow is a target of the pre-emption procedures/processes of the NG-RAN node.

section_list.name: QoS Flow List with Cause
aoa: 9.3.1.13 QoS Flow Item IE Semantics: This IE contains a list of QoS flows with a cause value. It is used for example to indicate failed QoS flow(s) or QoS flow(s) to be released.
9.3.1.51 QoS Flow Identifier - Section Description: This IE identifies a QoS flow within a PDU Session. The definition and use of the QoS Flow Identifier is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.2 Cause - Section Description: The purpose of the Cause IE is to indicate the reason for a particular event for the NGAP protocol.

section_list.name: Trace Activation
aoa: This IE defines parameters related to a trace session activation.

9.3.1.14 NG-RAN Trace ID IE Semantics: This IE is composed of the following: Trace Reference defined in TS 32.422 [11] (leftmost 6 octets, with PLMN information encoded as in 9.3.3.1), and Trace Recording Session Reference defined in TS 32.422 [11] (last 2 octets).

9.3.1.14 Interfaces to Trace IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an NG-RAN node interface: first bit = NG-C, second bit = Xn-C, third bit = Uu, fourth bit = F1-C, fifth bit = E1: other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates 'should be traced'. Value '0' indicates 'should not be traced'.
ENUMERATED (minimum, medium, maximum, minimumWithoutVendorSpecificExtension, mediumWithoutVendorSpecificExtension, maximumWithoutVendorSpecificExtension, …)
9.3.1.14 Trace Depth IE Semantics: Defined in TS 32.422 [11].

9.3.1.14 Trace Collection Entity IP Address IE Semantics: For File based Reporting. Defined in TS 32.422 [11]. This IE is ignored if the Trace Collection Entity URI IE is present. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].
9.3.1.167 MDT Configuration - Section Description: This IE defines the MDT configuration parameters.
9.3.1.169 MDT Configuration-NR - Section Description: This IE defines the MDT configuration parameters of NR.
ENUMERATED (Immediate MDT only, Logged MDT only, Immediate MDT and Trace, …)

Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.169 TAC IE Semantics: The TAI is derived using the current serving PLMN. 9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.169 Measurements to Activate IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap indicates a MDT measurement, as defined in TS 37.320 [41]. First Bit = M1, Second Bit= M2, Third Bit = M4, Fourth Bit = M5, Fifth Bit = M6, Sixth Bit = M7, Seventh Bit = logging of M1 from event triggered measurement reports according to existing RRM configuration, other bits reserved for future use. Value “1” indicates “activate” and value “0” indicates “do not activate”.

Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.
